<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 93 / International Company News: Publishing operations lift
earnings at Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PARAMOUNT Commun-ications, the US media group rumoured to be considering a
merger with Viacom Communications, has posted first-quarter net earnings of
Dollars 120.4m, or Dollars 1.01 a share.
A year earlier, the publishing, entertainment and theme parks group earned
Dollars 114.3m or 96 cents. Revenues rose to Dollars 1.35bn from Dollars
1.06bn. The gain was led by near-record operating income from Paramount's
publishing side and from sharply higher returns from its entertainment
business.
On Wall Street, shares in Paramount rose Dollars 4 1/4 to close at Dollars
61 1/8 . The stock gained Dollars 1 7/8 on Thursday amid speculation that
Paramount was discussing a stock-swap with Viacom which would value
Paramount at about Dollars 60 a share. The companies would not comment on
the rumours, but it is believed that Mr Martin Davis, Paramount's chairman
and chief executive has had informal discussions with Viacom's chairman Mr
Sumner Redstone, for several years.
Paramount has been looking for a merger partner since 1989, when its Dollars
200-a-share bid for Time failed.
A merger between Paramount and Viacom would create a company with extensive
cable and broadcast operationsas well as film and publishing businesses.
Paramount, with 1992 revenues of Dollars 4.27bn, owns a leading film studio
and television production company, as well as the Simon &amp; Schuster book
publishing house and New York's Madison Square Garden sports arena.
Viacom, with 1992 revenues of Dollars 1.86bn, is one of the most powerful
players in cable television. Its networks include MTV, Nickelodeon and
Showtime. Viacom is expanding overseas. MTV has recently entered Japanese
and Latin American markets, and has a growing presence in Europe. The
company also has an impressive television library of classic American TV
shows.
Paramount's entertainment division posted first-quarter operating income of
Dollars 89m, up from Dollars 60.8m. Results benefited from box-office
successes such as The Firm and Indecent Proposal. Paramount said its
entertainment results also benefited from higher operating income from its
theme parks.
Analysts at Salomon Brothers noted that half of the revenue gain and about
75 per cent of the operating profit rise came from Paramount's four domestic
and one international theme parks, acquired late last year.
But Madison Square Garden deepened its seasonal loss. The publishing
division posted record revenues for the quarter, led by strong gains from
its educational books.
Operating income from television programming fell in the quarter. Although
syndication sales of popular shows such as Cheers and Star Trek: the Next
Generation advanced, results at Paramount's jointly-owned cable operation,
USA Networks declined.
</TEXT>
