<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 93 / Roxburghe loses fight to save banking licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England has won its fight to revoke the licence of Roxburghe
Bank, the Asian bank that went into administration in April.
The decision follows an appeal against the Bank's petition brought by the
shareholders of Roxburghe, who initially demanded that the case be reviewed
by the banking appeals tribunal.
After initial discussions they agreed in the last few weeks not to proceed
with the appeal, the costs of which might have been charged to Roxburghe if
they had lost.
The details are revealed in a letter to be sent to the bank's 1,300
creditors early next week by Mr Tony Lomas and Mr Colin Bird, the joint
administrators from accountants Price Waterhouse.
Removing Roxburghe's authorisation to operate as a bank means that it has no
prospect of emerging from administration procedure to trade as a bank in the
future.
It also means that if the company is to continue to trade in some other
form, it will have to change its name in the next few months to remove the
word 'bank' from the title.
Mr J H Shah and Mr R H Shah, two directors, are believed to be considering
continuing their fight against aspects of the Bank of England's petition.
The Bank petitioned for Roxburghe's administration after monitoring its
position for some months.
The administrators said much of Roxburghe's business was with relatively
high-risk borrowers. Most of the depositors were from overseas,
predominantly based in India and Kenya, and many held deposits for
relatively small amounts.
They estimate that Roxburghe has assets of about Pounds 34m and liabilities
of Pounds 32m after provisions. Further provisions may give it negative net
worth of up to Pounds 5m, reducing the dividend to creditors below 100 per
cent.
Roxburghe is the fourth bank serving the Asian community in the UK to have
been affected since the collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International in 1991.
Mount Banking, which recently made a voluntary arrangement with its
creditors, is currently appealing against the Bank of England's petition for
withdrawal of its banking licence.
</TEXT>
