<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 93 / French growth seen next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French economy should emerge from recession in the final quarter of this
year and stage a recovery in 1994, according to the latest analysis by Bipe,
a leading economics institute, writes Alice Rawsthorn in Paris.
Bipe expects the recovery to start slowly in the first quarter of 1994 and
to gain momentum through the year. It sees GDP growth of 0.8 per cent
(excluding invisible earnings) for 1994, following a fall of 1.5 per cent in
1993.
The general trends in Bipe's forecast are similar to those outlined earlier
this week by the Economy Ministry. However, the institute is less optimistic
about the pace of recovery. The ministry expects growth (including invisible
earnings) of 1.4 per cent for 1994.
Retail prices were static in August, according to provisional figures
published yesterday by Insee, the state statistics institute, bringing the
annualised inflation rate to 2.2 per cent.
</TEXT>
