<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Record volume in Glaxo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRUGS group Glaxo stunned the investment community with a generous dividend
payment, prompting a rush of buying that left the shares up 27p at the
close. The rise accounted for 5.32 points on the FT-SE 100 Index. It was
accompanied by turnover of 24m shares, which matched the record volume and
sharp share falls registered in March when Dr Ernest Mario, the former chief
executive, resigned.
Yesterday, Dr Richard Sykes, Dr Mario's replacement, took advantage of an
increase in the company's cash pile to Pounds 1.8bn to flag his first
results presentation with a dividend of 22p, against expectations of around
20p. Glaxo had previously said it would not allow dividend cover to fall
below two times but yesterday's payout took cover to 1.8 times and the
company said it would be prepared to see it fall further.
Analysts who had been very cautious on the stock, including the
pharmaceuticals teams at James Capel and Lehman Brothers, were taken by
surprise.
Capel kept its current year profits forecast at Pounds 1.92bn but raised its
dividend prediction from 23p to 26p a share and moved to a 'hold' from a
'sell' stance. Lehman increased its profits estimate by Pounds 35m to Pounds
1.925bn.
Meanwhile, SG Warburg turned buyer and Mr James Culverwell of Hoare Govett,
already a buyer on yield considerations, said: 'People have overlooked the
capacity for the company to pay a dividend even when the outlook is
uncertain.'
Glaxo shares raced ahead 40 on the news and consolidated to close a net 27
up at 628p.
</TEXT>
