<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Weather slashes US maize crop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FLOODS in the US Midwest and drought in the south-east have slashed US maize
production to three-quarters of last year's levels, the Agriculture
Department said yesterday.
In its latest crop report the department estimated maize production at
7.23bn bushels compared with last year's record of 9.48bn. Yields were
estimated at 113.1 bushels per acre - 18.3 bushels below last year's record
of 131.4.
The weather did less to reduce wheat production. The department estimated
this year's output at 2.49bn bushels compared with 2.46bn last year.
However, there have been widespread reports of disease problems in the Red
River Valley of both Minnesota and North Dakota, as well as damage caused by
moisture in South Dakota. The National Association of Wheat Growers has
written to Mr Mike Espy, agriculture secretary, to express concern about
'serious wheat quality problems'.
The group is requesting establishment of a feed wheat purchase and donation
programme. It has also warned that damage may begin to appear in export
cargoes.
Despite the damage this year's wheat crop is expected to swell surplus
stocks. Because China and Russia have been largely absent from the world
market, the USDA has cut its wheat export projection to 1.35m bushels. The
figure last year was 50m.
US soyabean production will be an estimated 1.9bn bushels, about 13 per cent
below last year and the lowest output since 1988.
Cotton production is estimated at 17.9m bales, a rise of 10 per cent on last
year despite lack of rain in cotton-growing regions.
