<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / International Company News: Asian deal for Canada mine
groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CAMECO and Uranerz, Canada's biggest uranium producers, have signed a joint
10-year marketing and technical development agreement with Katep, the
uranium producer controlled by the Republic of Kazakhstan.
As a first step, the Canadian companies will invest USDollars 3m in Katep's
uranium facilities to improve efficiency, safety and environmental
performance. Acting as agents, they will help Katep sell its uranium
concentrates on long-term contract to world customers.
Katep has considerable uranium ore and also extensive in situ leachable
resources. Cameco produced 5,200 tonnes of uranium oxide last year, and
German-owned Uranerz 2,600 tonnes.
Their mines are in northern Saskatchewan. Their capacity, plus Katep's,
represent 30 per cent of world produc-tion.
Cameco, now 51.5 per cent-held by the public, is carrying out a feasibility
study of the Kumtor gold deposit in Kyrgyzstan, another former Asian
republic of the old Soviet Union.
Cominco reached agreement with 2,000 members of the United Steelworkers at
its lead-zinc operations in Trail, British Columbia. It covers job
flexibility and security, contracting out and job cuts through attrition.
</TEXT>
