<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / UK Company News: ICD attacks rival firm's vote buy-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SMALL marketing services company yesterday hit back at a rival which has
bought the voting rights of 23 per cent of its equity, saying the deal
breaches takeover panel rules.
USM-quoted International Communications and Data, which expects to announce
a pre-tax loss for the year to May 31 of Pounds 5m in the next two weeks
following a reorganisation, said the investment was unwelcome. Its shares
closed up 1 1/2 p at 13p yesterday.
ICD said that an investor group led by PSB Group, a direct marketing
company, had paid Pounds 100,000 for 2 per cent of ICD's equity at 5p a
share and the voting rights for six months on a further 21 per cent of the
equity. Of those shares, it has an option to buy for 14p each share
representing 13 per cent of the equity.
Mr David Cicurel, ICD's chairman, said: 'They have a lot of votes for very
little money risk and I would jolly well hope they have the interests of all
shareholders at heart.' PSB got its new interests from Mr Nigel Balcombe and
Mr John Apthorp, a former ICD chairman and director.
</TEXT>
