<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Clarke pledges review of funding for industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE, the chancellor, last night announced a review of the role
of financial institutions in funding industry, in particular small
businesses.
The review, to be carried out by Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to
the Treasury, will focus on whether business has access to the funds it
needs.
The chancellor told the annual dinner of the Confederation of British
Industry in Glasgow that he was concerned to ensure that the City and other
financial institutions contributed fully to the development of commerce and
industry.
The review is the first fruit of Mr Clarke's speech at the Mansion House in
June, in which he committed the Treasury to listen more to the concerns of
business. It also reflects the government's desire to ensure that the needs
of industry are at the forefront of policy-making.
The chancellor also announced measures to push forward the government's
private finance initiative, launched last year to attract private capital
for public-sector projects. A task force representing the public and private
sectors is to be formed to identify suitable projects and willing investors.
The initiative has attracted criticism for the lack of progress since it was
announced in the Autumn Statement. Many companies are reluctant to commit
resources to devising schemes to build new infrastructure, since they might
not win a contract when it goes out to tender.
Mr Nelson's review of funding for industry will aim to identify 'whether
there are any market imperfections which may distort the flows of finance',
according to the chancellor.
Among the issues to be reviewed will be the reliance of small and
medium-sized companies on bank overdrafts, which provide less flexibility
than types of finance available to businesses in other European countries.
Mr Nelson will also listen to complaints of 'short-termism' among
institutional investors, which refuse to adopt a long-term perspective in
funding growing businesses.
He will be keen to establish whether the market is failing to provide
finance to businesses with good investment potential.
The economic secretary is not expected to produce a report, the Treasury
said last night. However, it said that if problems are identified, the
government will take action to rectify them.
</TEXT>
