<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Press complaints body plans to resign if ombudsman appointed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD McGregor and the other members of the Press Complaints Commission plan
to resign en masse if the government imposes an ombudsman to deal with
complaints against newspapers.
The government is pushing ahead with proposals for an ombudsman with the
power to award compensation to victims of press intrusion.
Proposals are also well advanced to create new criminal offences covering
electronic eavesdropping and taking pictures on private property, with
tightly constrained public-interest defences. The Lord Chancellor's Office
has also proposed a new law giving citizens the right to sue for up to
Pounds 10,000 in damages for invasion of privacy.
The stage now looks set for a bitter confrontation between press and
government. Lord McGregor, chairman of the Press Council's replacement, has
said he will resign on the day an ombudsman is appointed, as self-regulation
of the press would be fatally weakened. His fellow commission members take a
similar view.
There has been considerable confusion and disagreement in the government on
press regulation in the wake of complaints about intrusion into the lives of
politicians and the royal family.
A white paper due from the Department of National Heritage before the summer
parliamentary recess failed to appear.
One of those involved said: 'We are waiting for a majority view to emerge.'
A consensus seems to be forming around the idea of the 'voluntary' ombudsman
who would hear appeals from those dissatisfied with commission verdicts. The
commission is paid for by the newspaper industry but now has a majority of
independent members.
The newspaper industry has said it will neither accept nor pay for such an
ombudsman.
Mr Dugal Nisbet-Smith, director of the Newspaper Society, the body
representing local and regional newspapers, said: 'It is an utterly, utterly
absurd idea. It will be opposed by every newspaper in the country.'
</TEXT>
