<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: BTR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There are real reasons for disappointment with BTR's first half results. The
operating margin has fallen; profit before interest would also be down
without the effect of exchange rate changes. But BTR's failure to deliver
strong organic growth only adds to the impression that it looks in need of
an acquisition again.
Unlike Williams, whose results also disappointed earlier this week, BTR's
balance sheet is increasingly able to support such a move. Gearing has
fallen by 8 percentage points since December. The disposal of Newey &amp; Eyre
and the enhanced scrip dividend will reduce it by about 12 points more. A
year from now the cash outlay on restructuring acquisitions could have
dwindled to a trickle.
Yet, if an acquisition looks both desirable and affordable, a suitable
target may be hard to find. At current market levels a contested bid for a
listed company could be prohibitively expensive. Shopping for an agreed
trade purchase might not yield anything large enough. The most interesting
opportunities could lie overseas. BTR's enhanced scrip dividend would make
greater sense if it reflected a realisation that an even larger proportion
of future earnings would be generated abroad.
</TEXT>
